I recommend their seafood selection but NOT their meats. Scallop, main lobster, crab salad and crab risotto dishes were AMAZING! Bison, duck and filet beef were okay.. but not worth picking it as your entree compared to the seafood dishes. The seafood dishes were cooked to perfection and the sauces accompanied with it was light and fresh. It's a perfect balance. Must pick! Don't get me wrong, I am a meat lover but Gary Danko didn't do it for me here. Ordered 5 courses and it was more than enough food for me! Service was great. Water glass and bread plate were never empty. However, we didn't get the anniversary cake. We did get the complimentary dessert platter though. Isn't it both or is it either or?

Now... I'm a pretty simple girl, and to be quite frank, I wouldn't enjoy a hundered dollar meal any more than I would enjoy a ten dollar one. Plus, I like to be comfortable and sometimes I feel a little claustrophobic when *too* much attention is paid to me... However, for our trip to San Francisco, the boyfriend and I decided that we would put on our fancy pants for a night and go out! We scoured the choices, and thumbed through the Yelp reviews, and promptly made reservations for Gary Danko's. From there, the love affair begins. Service here is PHENOMENAL. From the moment we arrived, til we were headed out the door, I felt like a little princess being catered to. Every single person on the staff is so friendly and accomodating. And to note, not a bit overbeaing. I opted for the three course, though for a quick minute I was tempted to get the four... and maybe even the five. The menu is broad and offers choices for whatever you might be craving for at the time. I wanted to sample it all.... But when it comes down to it, three is the perfect amount of food. If I could have grown an extra stomach on demand though, I would have went for the four. My descriptions of the food won't ever do those dishes justice, but I'll certain try to take a whack at it... The lobster risotto was the #1 dish I knew I needed to try if I was coming here. Absolutely amazing. Succulent chunks of lobster in a hearty, warm, savory risotto was pure bliss. Is it inapproriate to lick the bowl.....? Kidding... Maybe. The seared scallops were fantastic. Delicate, nice and crsip on the outside and tender on the inside. No funky tasting scallop pieces. Just pure, absolute deliciousness. If I'm going to be honest here, the lemon pepper duck was probably my least favorite dish. Now, not saying that it wasn't good, because it certainly was, but there wasn't anything that truly blew me away here. The duck was tender, and the flavors were satifying. Along with the accompanying hash, and bacon braised endive and pears, I think that there might have just been a little too much going on for me here after trying two relatively simple dishes prior. The boyfriend got 4 courses, so I of course helped myself to his dessert... He ordered the choclate souffle. These came with a duo of sauces, and while the server said we can choose one, he recommended both. Pour away! This was delicious, mindblowingly light for a chocolate desert and a perfect way to end the pefect meal. However, Gary Danko had something else in mind. After we finished our souffle, our sever brought out a nice surprise of little tastes! Bite sized pieces of various tarts, cakes, and what not. Small and sweet, but definitely memorable gesture. As we got ready to leave, the waiters had another surprise up their sleeves. They handed us even more food...! While the boyfriend was handed the check, I was given a cutely wrapped to-go pumpkin bread for breakfast the next morning. I little part of me wanted to hang onto it forever, as a little reminder of our amazing meal. Sentimental, and a little gross, I know. Don't worry, I ate it the next morning and it was a delicious reminder of the amazing meal we had the night before. I don't even like pumpkin and I ate it all up. That good. The food was amazing, and the service truly made the night a memorable one. Truly, I'd give Gary Danko's 10 stars if I could.

Excellent menu with lots of choices. First class quick efficient service. Only negative was wine prices for single glasses(5oz) and full bottles which were substantially higher than at other comparable restaurants.

CHOCOLATE SOUFFLE HEAVEN ```````````````````````````````````````````` AN ANGELIC UBER LUX TREAT AT UBER PRICES...... BUT SO WORTH IT, IF YOU CAN AFFORD IT! ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ Pretty much, every time I am in the SF area, I crave yet another excuse to go to Gary's. I usually stay right down the street at the SF Hyatt Fisherman's Wharf....and if I get a comp upgrade to the President Suite....all the more pleasure. Is it crowded, cramped, and possibly overrated.....some may think so....but I over-look all the distractors, and with the help of amazingly friendly & attentive staff, I usually order like 5-6 courses, plus the caviar, champagne (or a fine wine), and 1-2 Soufflés.... and that is just for me! And if they are too crowded to get a table, I am not above "Slumming" it at the Bar :).... they are even wonderful there! Now I do agree that the dishes can vary from the rare just OK, to the fantastic, but when you order like me....it all averages out to an amazing feast.... is my feast pricey....well lets just say that it can easily run from $200-500 depending upon my choices....so yes, it is a pricey treat....but I feel it is so worth it! AND more importantly, I am worth it! :) I first discovered Gary's when I have to go for my first Pre-op for my MAJOR SPINE SURGERY at UCSF a few years ago. It was also the only place that I could find on Yelp that made amazing Soufflés...and at least two or three flavors, too boot! My wonderful wife first feel in love with a Chocolate Soufflés at the Carmel Hyatt's X-mas Dinner a few years back...and since then we always look for something so excellent! Back before my surgery, even though I could barely walk, had a cane, was in severe pain & handicapped & had no reservation ...somehow discussions between the Hyatt concierge & Gary's Manager made it happen almost instantly, seemingly by magic, on my Pre-op Spine Surgery special night. They warmly greeted & expected me, despite my back-brace, my cane, and my sneakers....and made me feel so special, as I prepared for the most major critical event of my life.....a Spine Surgery to help save my life, the use of my legs, reduce my agony, & help my sanity! I will be so ever grateful for such compassionate kindness shown by them on that critical night! I felt that they were transformed from ordinary people to extraordinary people, who appeared as virtual Saints to me, as I struggled with the Herculean task of dealing with my extreme agony, my fateful decision, & the possibility of having my last meal either alive,or not paralyzed! They showed a compassionate kindness for the handicapped that I had not seen anywhere else....ever! To Gary's Wonderful Saintly Staff: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ THANK YOU SO VERY MUCH & BLESS YOU! :) ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ YOU ALL REALLY "PAYED IT FORWARD"! ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ Afterwards, I made it a point to return to Gary's for great dinners, whenever I was due for a follow-up with my great Orthopedic Surgeon, Dr. Serena Hu, at UCSF (who just moved from UCSF to Stanford). {BTW- UCSF Surgeon & OR was great, but the recovery room, post-op nursing care on the floor, was one of the most horrible experiences that I have ever known as a doctor/nurse & then a pathetic patient...it was too much trouble to even turn me...after 8 hours of non-care, I almost developed a pressure sore}. Since my experiences at Gary's were so intense, for such intense reasons, I avoided doing a review until now...when I am less biased. ~~~~Anyway, now that I am so much better, I still look for more excuses to go to Gary's....and will again this coming weekend..... I SO LOOK FORWARD TO THEIR WARM & WONDERFUL SERVICE.... not to mention....the AMAZING FOOD & SOUFFLES ! OMG!!!!!!! P.S.- I am totally biased, but I am still totally blissful every time I go!

Celebrated my birthday here last night (for the first time) with a few friends. What an exceptional experience. This place is an iconic SF spot for a reason. Some of the best service and food I've had. Susan (our server), Steven (the manager), and the wine som (looked like Russell Tovey--wish we had gotten his name) and Gregg (thanks for the tour of the kitchen!) were all charming, knowledgeable and gracious. I don't even know where to start so maybe I'll start off by saying this is the best dining experience I've had thus far. My bf took me here for my 25th birthday and aside from the food being amazing, the service was awesome. It's a nice place where you'll want to at least dress up a bit (think dress shirt for guys and a nice top for girls), but it doesn't have that stuffy uppity feel a lot of fine dining places have. There was plenty of parking a few blocks around the area, but if you want to do valet, it's only $12, so not a bad way to go. You basically get to customize your own tasting menu and you can pick either 3 courses for $73, 4 courses for $92, or 5 courses for $107. The courses can consist of anything from the menu so if you want 5 courses of all meat, go for it, but your waitress/waiter will probably recommend having a variety to balance things out. Additionally, they bring an amuse bouche before your first course comes out, and a small dessert and additional petit fours at the end to commemorate the special reason you are dining with them. Women will also receive a "breakfast pastry" to take home (mine was a pumpkin cake with cream cheese filling). We both opted for 4 courses and it was the perfect amount of food to be able to explore the menu. I got the Crispy Farm Egg, Lobster Risotto, Pork Tenderloin, and Chocolate Souffle in that order. Everything was delicious, but the one item that stood out the most was the Lobster Risotto. It consisted of huge chunks of fresh lobster that isn't overcooked, a bit of shrimp and butternut squash. The risotto itself was also cooked to the perfect consistency and the cream wasn't overly heavy. Although the chocolate souffle gets a lot of limelight in Yelp reviews, I think the chocolate and white chocolate sauces made the overall dessert too sweet and even a little mushy. My bf got the quail salad, duck, venison, and chocolate praline parfait. The venison was the favorite among the 4 dishes, as it was tender and not too gamey tasting and served on over a mushroom risotto. The quail salad however, was also notable because the quail was nicely flavored and crisped, but not too salty like quail and even other game birds tend to be. The dishes came out in a very timely fashion, where there was enough time in between each course to really take in the meal and enjoy yourself, but not too much of a lag where you're left feeling anxious or hungry for your next meal. Overall it was such a great experience that I would definitely recommend it to anyone celebrating special occasions or milestones. Just be sure to make your reservations 2 months in advance to ensure that you get the day/time you want!

Make sure to make reservations 2 months in advance! We came here 2/13 at 9:30 for our 10pm reservation & did valet parking for $15+tip. Upon entering, we were greeted by the host, checked in, and waited about 5 minutes until someone else came and took us to our table. We were asked if we wanted a wine or cocktail list & served our choice of water. One of the waiters came by and served us some bread (we got unlimited bread without having to ask until our plates were taken away). We ordered 2 Moscow mules which were delicious!! It was probably one of the best I've ever had- and I order them everywhere I go. So, how it works here is you are given the choice to order a 3,4, or 5 course meal. We originally were going to do the 5 course meal which was an appetizer, a meat course, seafood course, cheese plate, and dessert, but we got too stuffed mid meal so our server took the cheese course off our meal! To start, I ordered the seared foie gras which was amazing. It was perfectly buttery and the sauce that went along with it was perfect and did not overpower the dish. Next, I had the coconut Thai curry which came with scallops, shrimp, lobster, and calamari over a bed of rice. Not too sweet and the ice cream that came with it paired very well. I will definitely be back. Awesome food, awesome service.

I came here to celebrate my birthday. After reviewing various fine dining restaurants in the South Bay, I chose Gary Danko because of its high ratings and reviews. Gary Danko is okay, the food is okay, definitely not as refined as French Laundry or Picasso. I came here to celebrate and decided to go for the 5course. They offer very large portions, in fact after 3 courses i was almost full. Sadly the food did not impress me, the presentation was nice, food was very heavy and lacked flavor. Some dishes were good, while others failed to impress. Girlfriend and I sampled 10 different dishes to maximize our experience. We started with the seared foie gras, glazed oysters, and risotto. The oysters are quite tasty, a little heavy, definitely not as refined as french laundry or picasso. Guess i had too high expectations? Risotto was good, but again very heavy and salty. Foie gras was very good and rich, a very large portion, seared well. It was a very heavy and rich starter, they also gave big portions, so i would recommend not licking off your plates if you choose 5 courses. Moved on to seared bass, seared scallops and roasted lobster, they are very good options and well prepared. The scallop and lobster are my two favorite dishes of the night. The scallop was nicely seared with a good sauce compliment. Lobster was good too, but the proportion of mashed potato on bottom was way too much. Pan seared bass was flaky, buttery, but there was a fish bone in it! I almost swallowed a fish bone, not acceptable in my mind! Minus 1 star! For a 1 star Michelin restaurant, need better food prep, and cannot choke a customer on a fish bone. Ended with the stuffed quail and bison, both the meat dishes are disappointing me. The bison had very little flavor, super lean, definitely hard to chew and eat. Roasted quail was just a mish-mash of random ingredients would we could not distinguish while eating, and it did not blend well in my mind. The quail itself was very bland and dry. Lastly, we ended with the creme brulee trio and the chocolate souffle. The creme brulee is good, i liked the different flavor options. Souffle is definitely the winner! Very well made, fluffy, light, served straight out of the oven...just heavenly! I would probably come back just for their Souffle! So my experience was a little mixed, the seafood dishes seem to shine, while the meat dishes lacked flavor. Presentation for each dish is spot on, kudos to GD! Service was nice and attentive, almost too attentive, i don't need a waitress coming every 5min asking me how the food is, blah blah, etc... Would I come back? It depends who is paying, LOL! I would not come back and order 5 courses, probably stick with 4. The souffle was definitely the highlight of my meal, while meat dishes failed to impress me. And that darn fish bone was rather distracting in my fish dish! There are plenty of good restaurants in SF, a good experience at GD if you never been, but there are better restaurants in the city.

Having recently dined another Relais & Châteaux Restaurant - in New York, I have to admit I was a rather disappointed by the service and lack of attention to detail when we dined at Gary Danko last night. Twice my wine glass was empty (I was having by-the-glass) - and no one asked if I would like more - nor did they remove my empty glass for quite some time. I had to ask both times for another glass of wine. The food was underwhelming. The dessert we ordered was memorable and flavorful. The other courses did not astound me. They were good - but not at the level that I would have expected for a restaurant of this caliber. My husband and I both noticed 3 or 4 servers preparing a 5 top next to us for the next turn and honestly, we felt like there was more care and attention to detail in the servers setting up the table than we had experienced through out our meal. The other Relais & Châteaux Restaurant - in New York - was stellar and their service and attention to detail was impeccable. They paid attention to us and made us feel like our whole dining experience was something that they held in high regard. This is the way I prefer my dining experience to be for such a high price point at a restaurant that is considered be in the category of fine dining. Overall, for the price point and the expectation of a luxury meal - Gary Danko missed on many levels for us last evening. It was a disappointing and underwhelming experience.

    Now... I'm a pretty simple girl, and to be quite frank, I wouldn't enjoy a hundered dollar meal any more than I would enjoy a ten dollar one. Plus, I like to be comfortable and sometimes I feel a little claustrophobic when *too* much attention is paid to me... However, for our trip to San Francisco, the boyfriend and I decided that we would put on our fancy pants for a night and go out! We scoured the choices, and thumbed through the Yelp reviews, and promptly made reservations for Gary Danko's. From there, the love affair begins.

    Service here is PHENOMENAL. From the moment we arrived, til we were headed out the door, I felt like a little princess being catered to. Every single person on the staff is so friendly and accomodating. And to note, not a bit overbeaing.

    I opted for the three course, though for a quick minute I was tempted to get the four... and maybe even the five. The menu is broad and offers choices for whatever you might be craving for at the time. I wanted to sample it all.... But when it comes down to it, three is the perfect amount of food. If I could have grown an extra stomach on demand though, I would have went for the four.

    My descriptions of the food won't ever do those dishes justice, but I'll certain try to take a whack at it...

    The lobster risotto was the #1 dish I knew I needed to try if I was coming here. Absolutely amazing. Succulent chunks of lobster in a hearty, warm, savory risotto was pure bliss. Is it inapproriate to lick the bowl.....? Kidding... Maybe.

    The seared scallops were fantastic. Delicate, nice and crsip on the outside and tender on the inside. No funky tasting scallop pieces. Just pure, absolute deliciousness.

    If I'm going to be honest here, the lemon pepper duck was probably my least favorite dish. Now, not saying that it wasn't good, because it certainly was, but there wasn't anything that truly blew me away here. The duck was tender, and the flavors were satifying. Along with the accompanying hash, and bacon braised endive and pears, I think that there might have just been a little too much going on for me here after trying two relatively simple dishes prior.

    The boyfriend got 4 courses, so I of course helped myself to his dessert... He ordered the choclate souffle. These came with a duo of sauces, and while the server said we can choose one, he recommended both. Pour away! This was delicious, mindblowingly light for a chocolate desert and a perfect way to end the pefect meal. However, Gary Danko had something else in mind. After we finished our souffle, our sever brought out a nice surprise of little tastes! Bite sized pieces of various tarts, cakes, and what not. Small and sweet, but definitely memorable gesture.

    As we got ready to leave, the waiters had another surprise up their sleeves. They handed us even more food...! While the boyfriend was handed the check, I was given a cutely wrapped to-go pumpkin bread for breakfast the next morning. I little part of me wanted to hang onto it forever, as a little reminder of our amazing meal. Sentimental, and a little gross, I know. Don't worry, I ate it the next morning and it was a delicious reminder of the amazing meal we had the night before. I don't even like pumpkin and I ate it all up. That good.

    The food was amazing, and the service truly made the night a memorable one. Truly, I'd give Gary Danko's 10 stars if I could.

    I don't even know where to start so maybe I'll start off by saying this is the best dining experience I've had thus far. My bf took me here for my 25th birthday and aside from the food being amazing, the service was awesome. It's a nice place where you'll want to at least dress up a bit (think dress shirt for guys and a nice top for girls), but it doesn't have that stuffy uppity feel a lot of fine dining places have.

    There was plenty of parking a few blocks around the area, but if you want to do valet, it's only $12, so not a bad way to go.

    You basically get to customize your own tasting menu and you can pick either 3 courses for $73, 4 courses for $92, or 5 courses for $107. The courses can consist of anything from the menu so if you want 5 courses of all meat, go for it, but your waitress/waiter will probably recommend having a variety to balance things out. Additionally, they bring an amuse bouche before your first course comes out, and a small dessert and additional petit fours at the end to commemorate the special reason you are dining with them. Women will also receive a "breakfast pastry" to take home (mine was a pumpkin cake with cream cheese filling).

    We both opted for 4 courses and it was the perfect amount of food to be able to explore the menu. I got the Crispy Farm Egg, Lobster Risotto, Pork Tenderloin, and Chocolate Souffle in that order. Everything was delicious, but the one item that stood out the most was the Lobster Risotto. It consisted of huge chunks of fresh lobster that isn't overcooked, a bit of shrimp and butternut squash. The risotto itself was also cooked to the perfect consistency and the cream wasn't overly heavy. Although the chocolate souffle gets a lot of limelight in Yelp reviews, I think the chocolate and white chocolate sauces made the overall dessert too sweet and even a little mushy. My bf got the quail salad, duck, venison, and chocolate praline parfait. The venison was the favorite among the 4 dishes, as it was tender and not too gamey tasting and served on over a mushroom risotto. The quail salad however, was also notable because the quail was nicely flavored and crisped, but not too salty like quail and even other game birds tend to be.

    The dishes came out in a very timely fashion, where there was enough time in between each course to really take in the meal and enjoy yourself, but not too much of a lag where you're left feeling anxious or hungry for your next meal. Overall it was such a great experience that I would definitely recommend it to anyone celebrating special occasions or milestones. Just be sure to make your reservations 2 months in advance to ensure that you get the day/time you want!

    Gary Danko is okay, the food is okay, definitely not as refined as French Laundry or Picasso.  I came here to celebrate and decided to go for the 5course.  They offer very large portions, in fact after 3 courses i was almost full.  Sadly the food did not impress me, the presentation was nice, food was very heavy and lacked flavor.  Some dishes were good, while others failed to impress.

    Girlfriend and I sampled 10 different dishes to maximize our experience.  We started with the seared foie gras, glazed oysters, and risotto.  The oysters are quite tasty, a little heavy, definitely not as refined as french laundry or picasso.  Guess i had too high expectations?  Risotto was good, but again very heavy and salty.  Foie gras was very good and rich, a very large portion, seared well.  It was a very heavy and rich starter, they also gave big portions, so i would recommend not licking off your plates if you choose 5 courses.

    Moved on to seared bass, seared scallops and roasted lobster, they are very good options and well prepared.  The scallop and lobster are my two favorite dishes of the night.  The scallop was nicely seared with a good sauce compliment.  Lobster was good too, but the proportion of mashed potato on bottom was way too much.  

    Pan seared bass was flaky, buttery, but there was a fish bone in it!  I almost swallowed a fish bone, not acceptable in my mind!  Minus 1 star!  For a 1 star Michelin restaurant, need better food prep, and cannot choke a customer on a fish bone.  

    Ended with the stuffed quail and bison, both the meat dishes are disappointing me.  The bison had very little flavor, super lean, definitely hard to chew and eat.   Roasted quail was just a mish-mash of random ingredients would we could not distinguish while eating, and it did not blend well in my mind.  The quail itself was very bland and dry.

    Lastly, we ended with the creme brulee trio and the chocolate souffle.  The creme brulee is good, i liked the different flavor options.  Souffle is definitely the winner!  Very well made, fluffy, light, served straight out of the oven...just heavenly!  I would probably come back just for their Souffle!  

    So my experience was a little mixed, the seafood dishes seem to shine, while the meat dishes lacked flavor.  Presentation for each dish is spot on, kudos to GD!  Service was nice and attentive, almost too attentive, i don't need a waitress coming every 5min asking me how the food is, blah blah, etc...

    Would I come back?  It depends who is paying, LOL!  I would not come back and order 5 courses, probably stick with 4.  The souffle was definitely the highlight of my meal, while meat dishes failed to impress me.  And that darn fish bone was rather distracting in my fish dish!  There are plenty of good restaurants in SF, a good experience at GD if you never been, but there are better restaurants in the city.
